,Recommended,277590,14901347,"Posted: 15 March, 2015",all,ThatDarnOwl,"Freedom Cry is a bit of stand-alone DLC for AC4. You play as Adewale, your ship Quartermaster from AC4 turned Assassin. Who sets out on a quest of his own to liberate slaves in the Carribean.Freedom Cry does a lot to try and be different than AC4. For starters the game is more stealth focused. For much of the game you're liberating slaves from plantations by eliminating their overseers. And the player gets rewarded with new tools, upgrades and weapons for freeing more slaves. However if the player caught they begin to murder the slaves before you can free them. This creates an incentive to play as stealthily as possible and as a result there's significantly less of a combat focus. This was clearly intentional and you tend to only use your blowgun and hidden blades.As a result Freedom Cry feels significantly more like a stealth action game than any of the previous Assassin Creed games. And it's to it's credit. The only real gripes I have with it are the story is a bit lacking compared to AC4 and it doesn't take you that long to complete. It is priced pretty reasonably though and it's a blast to try and complete 100%.I highly recommend Freedom Cry. It complements AC4 nicely, and its more focused stealth gameplay is a welcome change."
,Recommended,277590,16562532,"Posted: 20 June, 2015",all,NMBR1MRTL,"You let out a cry of freedom as you returnhome from work, dead tired.It’s bad enough you’ve been juggling schooland a part-time job at the bookstore, inaddition to your growing relationship withthe beautiful Goth in the class, _Summer-Rain_.She’s been arguing with you lately.Logging in to Steam once more after draggingyour feet from the bath, you see a gamethat you don’t seem to remember:Assassin’s Creed: Freedom Cry.You vaguely recall that it focused on thesupporting character, Adewale; from thefourth title in the series, Black Flag, and itwas originally marketed as DLC beforebecoming a standalone title.Shrugging, you buy and soon install the game.You try not to think about the things youhad to put up with throughout the weekin the back of your head; that idiot bossyou hate but you need your job more,the school projects getting more mentallydemanding and _ Summer-Rain_ arguingwith you over a misunderstanding.Whether you’re a returning player fromBlack Flag or someone entirely new withno knowledge of the series, Freedom Cry’sstory is the main draw of the game, beingsimple, accessable and without any obviousbaggage from the previous games.Freedom Cry’s cast is limited to revolvingaround only four characters; Adewale himself,his person-of-interest; the beautiful BastienneJosephe, the local Madame of the Brothel inPort-Au-Prince, the evil Governeur De Fayetand the stoic Augustin Dieufort, leader of theMaroon Rebellion.Most of Assassin’s Creed: Black Flag is ondisplay at its finest here. The activities likewhaling for animal skins and crafting materialsreturn in a smaller capacity, the naval combatand free-running are top-notch as ever andthe graphics can bring an underequippedPC to ruin.You find yourself giggling as you see your idiotboss in the villainous Governeur De Fayet, andyou relish how satisfying it is to go aroundfreeing your brothers in chains while you killSlavers and soldiers who oppress and bully.Each mission or small side-quest you completebrings you closer to the real-world, so you canresume your responsibilities without the urge totake a machete into your boss’s face or kill yourclassmates for not doing enough in your groupprojects.Freedom Cry’s ending makes you pick upthe phone to apologize to _Summer-Rain_.She asks what brought about this change ofheart. You tell her about Freedom Cry.How you bought a game of prejudice, whichwas also with a means to fight it and the effortit came with to fight such things like prejudice,racism and slavery.How you bought newfound gratitude for yourlife and things you have. The things you tookfor granted, and the things you had taken forgranted.The people you had taken for granted.She responds, dabbing her eyes.“Let’s not fight... Not when we can playgames like the one you just finished.”You answer while smiling on the other end.“You’re right, Summer. Let Freedom Cry.”"
