76561198058804201,Recommended,277590,12494491,"Posted: 14 October, 2014",all,BenDover,"Freedom Cry is a short but sweet extra chapter of AC4: Black Flag that brings in just enough new interesting features to make it worth the price. You play as Adewale, Edward Kenway's Ex-First Mate. Most of the game is centered around freeing slaves, and the mid sized area you get to play around with is full of respawning side-missions to do like taking an injured to a safe spot set up by the maroon rebellion or saving a half dozen slaves being auctioned off with force or simplying buying them then letting them go free. Your main area is Port de Prince, a town full of activity, but after an hour of fooling around you will know the town like the back of your hand and done anything there is to do. You get a new ship at the start of the game, and I was happy to see Ubisoft made us a totally new slice of the Carribbean to explore, though another 2 hours and you'll have done literally everything. The bright side is there is a few awesome side missions to play. My favorite is the Plantation missions because of the different techniques to employ in getting the slaves out safely. Start a massive riot and hope to god you and the slaves overpower the overseers or thin the heard steath style until the enemy has only a few men left then swarm them. (It's basically warehouse missions from black flag but once the alarm is triggered you have to act fast because the overseers are outnumbere 4 to 1 by slaves so they start killing them right away after the alarm is trigggered) There are also slave ships which are heavily escorted but carry around 100 slaves but can't be damaged at all before borded (obviously). Adewale is a pretty cool guy but they don't really flesh him out beyond he's has to get back to the brotherhood eventually but he refuses to leave until the rebellion is strong enough to stand without him. The new weapons he gets to use are a nice refreshment though. His main weapons is a machete, and its a brutal weapon that gets the blood flying and seems to always get stuck in the bodies of slavemasters. The second and best new weapon is the blunderbluss, which adds a whole new element of gameplay, because now you can take out a concentrated group of soldiers with one shot. Overall a good game though just barely worth the asking price."
