,Not Recommended,277590,18214462,"Posted: 26 September, 2015",all,Double Uppercut,"Well, here we finally are. About f***ing time.It took me forever to get this game to work on my old laptop, but now I've finally loaded this thing up!.... On a separate laptop. With a much better graphics card. And processor.I could rant like I did before about Ubisoft being far too prissy about their graphics, but I'm sure anyone who did play this game actually read the system requirements. But I suppose I could get mad that Ubisoft also requires you install UPlay, their far inferior attempt to compete against Steam and Origin.Well, the store itself is pretty sh***y, but the Ubi30 free game deal is pretty sweet. And once you get UPlay actually up, the game starts and runs just fine... although it will remind you how fast the game is running in the top left corner as a default option. Just so the extreme PC Master Race freaks can reminds themselves what a great decision they made to depart from being console owners.The game looks good. The game plays good. But that's really because it's just Assassin's Creed IV condensed. Sure, it says ""Standalone Game"" in the pictures of it, but this is really just an inflated DLC pack. But still a better one than today's standard of DLCs.You play as Adewale as he fights against racism and slavery in the West Indies. You're given a small map to work with as Adewale or in his own pirate ship and crew. And that's all good and dandy, but how does the story fare?It's alright. Yeah, it's about racial discrimination, which is never the most subtle topic but it's still handled well in this story. The overall point isn't shoved in your face like some other racial stories. What I can't stand in this game was the requirement to gather slaves or perform menial tasks before unlocking the next story mission, which seems pretty foolish to me. It takes the focus away from the story and into the player just crossing off items on a checklist.I'm also not a fan of how in this game, like several later Assassin's Creed games can get with reserved acting. Even in the highest resolution and graphical settings, the characters in this story are just bland and not very expressive, so it makes cutscenes less engaging as a player.If you love Black Flag to death and want a little more story and some more gameplay mechanics, then this is definitely for you. But I'm still sticking with not recommending it for anyone who wants to play just this and nothing else. Black Flag felt more like a well-made meal, and Freedom Cry feels more like a desert that's filled with just some poorly-cooked vegetables. I'm giving Assassin's Creed: Freedom Cry a 5/10"
